         <abstract>
            <p>The weight assigned component companies in a market index changes as stock prices change. Depending how the index is calculated, weights may in effect be reapportioned continuously, periodically, or never. A geometric average of returns on component securities corresponds to continuous compounding, for example, while an average of monthly rates of return like the Fisher Index implies reallocation once a month. The cumulative impact of differences in the reallocation frequency can be surprisingly large.</p>
          </abstract>
